Blueprint

Target IP: 10.10.64.129

Hack into this Windows machine and escalate your privileges to Administrator.
Do you have what is takes to hack into this Windows Machine?

Reconnaissance


There are ten TCP ports open on the target machine, as shown above.


Doing an aggressive nmap scan against the different ports returns the result above. From the scan above, the HTTP application on port 8080 looks interesting to me as it contains the name and version oscommerce-2.3.4 of application.

Enumeration

Port 8080: HTTP

Browsing to http://10.10.64.129:8080 contains the interesting directory above. This is publicly disclosed and it should not be accessible.


Clicking the oscommerce-2.3.4 folder shows two more folders: catalog and docs.


Browsing to docs/ from the previous webpage returns the webpage above. This folder contains the documentation of the web application -- including the database schema and database itself.


The database_schema.mwb contains the database. However, I did not find anything useful here. I did not find any credentials. Time to enumerate further.


Browsing to catalog/ from the previous webpage returns the webpage above. It looks like a web application. Doing a Google search for this application version shows it is vulnerable to RCE.

Exploitation & Flag


I found the public exploit above on Github for this web application. I downloaded the exploit on my machine.


And firing the exploit against http://10.10.64.129:8080/oscommerce-2.3.4/catalog worked. Now I can perform RCE on the target machine. Time to upgrade this to a full reverse shell connection.


Using the shell from the exploit, I deployed a base64 encoded powershell reverse shell to connect to my machine on port 8443. This reverse shell connected to my machine on port 8443 and now I have a foothold on the target machine. This exploit spawns a session as nt authority\system, so I do not need to perform privilege escalation.


I copied the SAM and SYSTEM files to the Desktop of user Administrator.


Then I moved these files to C:\xampp\htdocs\oscommerce-2.3.4 so I can access it via the web browser at http://10.10.64.129:8080/oscommerce-2.3.4/.


Now I can access the SAM and SYSTEM files directly. I downloaded these files on my machine. Now I can use impacket to view the contents. I downloaded these files on my machine. After downloading it, I used rm to delete the two files.


And bingo! Now I have the password hashes of the users of the system.


The next goal is to crack the NTLM hash of user LAB. Using crackstation, I obtained the password googleplus after cracking the hash.


The root flag shown above which is located at Desktop of user Administrator. GG.
